
Dependency Injection (DI) in Java is a design pattern in which the objects that a class needs (dependencies) are provided from outside the class instead of the class creating them itself.

Definition

Dependency Injection is a technique where one object supplies the dependencies of another object, making the code more flexible, reusable, and easier to test.



Advantages of Dependency Injection

Loose Coupling – Classes are less dependent on each other.
Easy Testing – Mock objects can be injected during testing.
Better Code Reusability – Components can be reused easily.
Easy Maintenance – Changes in one class have less impact on others.

Types of Dependency Injection

Constructor Injection – Dependencies are passed through the constructor.
Setter Injection – Dependencies are passed using setter methods.
Field Injection – Dependencies are injected directly into fields (commonly used in Spring).
Interview Definition

Dependency Injection is a design pattern that provides an object's dependencies from an external source rather than creating them inside the object, promoting loose coupling and easier testing.